Student’s Behavior Analysis

Sonia Agarwal CS555(SUMMER O2) 8/18/2022

Research scenario and question(s)

The goal of the analysis is to draw assumptions regarding student activities such as:

  • Analysis of student’s behavior with different categorical variables finding answer.

  • Gender wise Who spend more time on studying on a daily basis?

  • Estimating the population mean of the College marks of students of universities by taking a random sample by using Central Limit Theorem.

  • Calculating Least squares regression(Multiple Regression) equation that predicts Average Student College Mark from Height(cm),Weight(kg) and 12th.Mark.Formally testing (using the 5-step procedure) whether the set of these predictors are associated with Average Student College Mark at the α = 0.05 by performing the Global test.

  • How many students are in each group? Summarize the data relating to both College.Mark and Department.

  • Do the Average College Mark vary by Department?

  • Perform a one way ANOVA using the aov or Anova function in R to assess. Use a significance level of α=0.05. Summarize the results using the 5-step procedure.

  • If the results of the overall model are significant, perform the appropriate pairwise comparisons using Tukey’s procedure to adjust for multiple comparisons and summarize these results.

Create an appropriate number of dummy variables for department and re-run the one-way ANOVA using the lm function with the newly created dummy variables. Set BCA department as the reference group.

Dataset Overview

The following data set contains information on 200+ university students. This data set is retrieved from Kaggle.This data set contains 19 different pieces of information such as gender, height, weight, 10th, 12th, grade, hobbies, daily study time, and more.

The data provided held a lot of valuable information. Here I created a new column named willingness for the purpose of changing character values with % sign to numeric data by taking 0.75 instead of 75%.I used Library(dplyr), library(plotly),library(knitr) for my analysis.I have uploaded the csv file on my github account and I am referencing that in R code. Central Limit Theorem

To estimate the population mean of the College marks of students of universities by taking a random sample.

The Central Limit Theorem states that the distribution of the sample means for a given sample size of the population has the shape of the normal distribution. The theorem is shown with various distributions of the input data in the following sections.” In other words, as the sample size gets larger, the means of the samples become a normal distribution. This was tested against the Average Student College Marks. Below is a figure showing the distributions of 5000 random samples of sample sizes of 10, 20, 30, and 40 with replacement is true and showed that the applicability of the Central Limit Theorem for this variable.With samples sizes of 10, 20, 30, and 40 histogram of sample means is verified.

By looking at the plots it is more likely that as the size of samples increasing histogram is showing more normal distribution. It tells us that as size increases, the distribution will look more and more like the normal distribution and that the variability will reduce.

### Least squares regression(Multiple Regression)

Least squares regression(Multiple Regression) equation that predicts Average Student College Mark from Height(cm),Weight(kg) and 12th.Mark.

When fitting a multiple regression model, understanding the associations between each of the independent variables Height(cm),Weight(kg) and 12th.Mark with the dependent variable College Mark as well as the associations between independent variables is important. Let’s first look at a scatter plot matrix for Height(cm),Weight(kg) and 12th.Mark with the dependent variable College Mark.

It can be seen from the graph and the correlation output values - There is weak association (0.27594837) between Height and Weight of the students.

  • There is negligible to the negative side association (-0.12067154) between height and 12th marks.

  • There is negligible to the negative side association (-0.01853459) between height and college marks.

  • There is negligible to the negative side association (-0.01920847) between Weight and college marks.

  • There is negligible to the negative side association (-0.01490092) between height and college marks.

  • There is a weak association (0.42512280) between college.mark and 12th mark.

Least square regression equation

ŷ=25.22504 + 0.02779xHeight + -0.01810xWeight + 0.61299x12thMark

The regression equation’s main function is to predict the average or expected value of the Collge marks and the help understand the relationship. There is still randomness and variability in the response that plays into the actual response

Using summary(m) the value of adjusted R2 is 0.1715. Means there is, 17.15% of the variability that college marks can be explained by Height,weight and 12th marks of the student.

Hypothesis Testing (Test if set of these predictors are associated with College marks score at the α = 0.05.)

  1. Set up the hypotheses and select the alpha level This is equivalent to test whether all predictors combined can explained a significant portion of the variance of the outcome variable • H0 : βcollegemarks= βheight = βweight = β12th marks =0 (there is no linear association) • H1: βi≠0 for i = college marks, height, weight and 12th marks (there is a linear association, at least one of the slope coefficients is different than 0) • α=0.05

  2. Select the appropriate test statistic

F=MS Reg/MS Res df = 3,n−k−1

  1. State the decision rule

• Determine the appropriate value from the F-distribution table with 3,n−k−1=235−3−1=231 degrees of freedom and associated with a right hand tail probability of α=0.05 • Using the table, Fk,n−k−1,α=F3,98,0.05=2.64

qf(0.95,df1=3,df2=231)

• Decision Rule: Reject H0 if F ≥ 2.64368 • Otherwise, do not reject H0

  1. Compute the test statistic

    F value from the summary(m) F-statistic: 17.14 p-value: 0.0000000004374.

  2. Conclusion Reject H0 since 17.14 ≥ 2.64368. We have significant evidence at the α=0.05 level that there is at least one slope coefficient that is different than zero. That is, there is evidence of a significant linear association between set of predictors with college marks. Here p<0.001 as calculated using software program). Using summary(m) the value of adjusted R2 is 0.1715. Means there is, 17.15% of the variability that college marks can be explained by Height, weight and 12th marks of students.

Interpretation for 12th marks as Predictor after adjusting for height and weight

Using Global F test and the table above, since 𝑝(0000000000105) ≤ 𝛼. We have significant evidence at the α=0.05 level that β12th marks ≠0 after controlling for height and weight. That is, 12th marks is a significant predictor of college marks after adjusting for height and weight (here, p<0.0001 as calculated using software program).

##              Df Sum Sq Mean Sq F value      Pr(>F)    
## Depart        3   7290    2430    11.1 0.000000785 ***
## Residuals   231  50590     219                        
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

We can see that the overall p-value from the ANOVA table is 0.000000785. Since this is less than .05, we have sufficient evidence to say that the mean values across each departments are not equal. Thus, we can proceed to perform Tukey’s Test to determine exactly which department means are different.

5-step procedure

  1. Set up the hypotheses and select the alpha level

• H0:μB.com Accounting and Finance =μBCC =μCommerce= μB.com ISM (All underlying population means are equal) • H1:μi≠μj for some i and j (Not all of the underlying population means are equal) • α=0.05

  1. Select the appropriate test statistic • F=MSB/MSW

  2. State the decision rule • Determine the appropriate value from the F-distribution with k−1=4−1=3, n−k=235−3=232 degrees of freedom and associated with a right-hand tail probability of α=0.05 • Using software, Fk−1, n−k, α=F3, 232, 0.05 =2.643511 (since exact combination not available on table) • Decision Rule: Reject H0 if F ≥ 2.643511 • Otherwise, do not reject H0 # Using R code qf(0.95,df1=3,df2=232)

  3. Compute the test statistic Using One way ANOVA table F=MSB/MSW ≈ 11.1

  4. Conclusion Reject H0 since 11.1 ≥ 2.643511 We have significant evidence at the α=0.05 level not all of the underlying population means are equal (here, p(0.000000785) <0.001 as calculated using a software program). So, these departments are different in their average college marks.

As the results of the overall model are significant (null hypothesis is rejected), so we can perform the additional steps to determine which of the population Department means are different by using appropriate pairwise comparisons using Tukey’s procedure to adjust for multiple comparisons. Our confidence level to be 95%, which means we want our family-wise error rate to be 0.05. R gives us two metrics to compare each pairwise difference: 1. Confidence interval for the mean difference (given by the values of lwr and upr) 2. Adjusted p-value for the mean difference

Pairwise t-test

Post-hoc test TukeyHSD - Test which of the groups have different means

Interpretation

Commerce-BCA The 95% confidence interval for the mean difference between Commerce department and BCA department is (-20.9014825, 3.606244), and this interval contains zero so the difference between these two departments means is not statistically significant. Likewise, the adjusted p-value for the mean difference between Commerce department and BCA department is 0.2636405, which is greater than our significance level of 0.05, so this also indicates that the difference between these two departments means is not statistically significant.

B.com Accounting and Finance-BCA The 95% confidence interval for the mean difference between B.com Accounting and Finance and BCA is (-8.4483387, 12.421521), and this interval contains zero so the difference between these two departments means is not statistically significant. Likewise, the adjusted p-value for the mean difference between Commerce department and BCA department is 0.9606679 which is greater than our significance level of 0.05, so this also indicates that the difference between these two departments means is not statistically significant.

B.com ISM-BCA The 95% confidence interval for the mean difference between B.com ISM and BCA is (-0.7086918, 21.402025), and this interval contains zero so the difference between these two departments means is not statistically significant. Likewise, the adjusted p-value for the mean difference between B.com ISM and BCA department is 0.0757895 which is greater than our significance level of 0.05, so this also indicates that the difference between these two departments means is not statistically significant.

Accounting and Finance-Commerce The 95% confidence interval for the mean difference between Accounting and Finance and Commerce department is (2.6660607, 18.602359), and since this interval doesn’t contain zero we know that the difference between these two departments means is statistically significant.Likewise, the adjusted p-value for the mean difference between Accounting and Finance and Commerce is 0.0036528, which is less than our significance level of 0.05, so this also indicates that the difference between these two department means is statistically significant.

B.com ISM-Commerce

The 95% confidence interval for the mean difference between B.com ISM and Commerce department is (10.2293215, 27.759250), and since this interval doesn’t contain zero we know that the difference between these two departments means is statistically significant.Likewise, the adjusted p-value for the mean difference between B.com ISM-Commerce is 0.0000003, which is less than our significance level of 0.05, so this also indicates that the difference between these two department means is statistically significant.

B.com ISM-B.com Accounting and Finance The 95% confidence interval for the mean difference between B.com ISM-B.com Accounting and Finance department is (2.3972588, 14.322893), and since this interval doesn’t contain zero we know that the difference between these two departments means is statistically significant.Likewise, the adjusted p-value for the mean difference between B.com ISM-B.com Accounting and Finance is 0.0019804, which is less than our significance level of 0.05, so this also indicates that the difference between these two department means is statistically significant.

Creating an appropriate number of dummy variables

Create an appropriate number of dummy variables for department and re-run the one-way ANOVA using the lm function with the newly created dummy variables. Set BCA department as the reference group.

First need to create the dummy variables. We need (# of departments - 1)3 dummy variables.

The regression model in this case taking BCA department as reference group is given by

y = 67.933+ 1.987DepartmentBCAccounting +10.347 DepartmentBCISM -8.648DepartmentCommerce

The intercept β0 (the sample mean in the reference group i. e.BCA department is 67.933 when all the other departments having value zero. The estimated difference in department mean between BCA Accounting and reference department BCA is 1.987 and the t value is 0.493. p-value for the mean difference between BCA Accounting and reference department BCA is 0.6227, which is not statistically significant.

The estimated difference in department mean between B.COM ISM and reference department BCA is 10.347 and the t value is 2.422. p-value for the mean difference between B.COM ISM and reference department BCA is 0.0162, which is statistically significant. The estimated difference in department mean between Commerce and reference department BCA is -8.648 and the t value is -1.826. p-value for the mean difference between Commerce and reference department BCA is 0.0691, which is not statistically significant.It is slightly deviated from the alpha value 0.05.

Adjusted r squared value is 0.1146 which is telling that linear model explains 11.46% of the variability.It is not explaining much about the variability between the departments.

Conclusion

There are some outliers and after removing the outliers there is slight change in R squared value. It means they have influence on the data. The adjusted R2 is 0.1715. Means there is, 17.15% of the variability that college marks can be explained by Height,weight and 12th marks of the student.Adjusted r squared value is 0.1146 which is telling that linear model explains 11.46% of the variability.It is not explaining much about the variability between the departments.I think both the cases model is not good model predictor for the college marks.
